00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:16.110 --> 00:00:18.220
&gt;&gt; Michelle Bickert: Thank you
everybody for joining us today

00:00:18.220 --> 00:00:20.440
and for moving down
closer to the front.

00:00:20.440 --> 00:00:23.520
We really appreciate it and
are happy to enjoy you and see

00:00:23.520 --> 00:00:25.120
if you're really, really excited

00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:28.390
or if you maybe make it easier
to throw tomatoes at us.

00:00:28.390 --> 00:00:29.690
I don't know.

00:00:29.690 --> 00:00:32.300
I hope everybody's having
a good DPLA Fest so far.

00:00:32.300 --> 00:00:41.040
Whoo! We are here to talk to
you today and give you an update

00:00:41.040 --> 00:00:42.860
on library ebook platforms.

00:00:42.860 --> 00:00:46.850
As some of you may remember
from last year we were able

00:00:46.850 --> 00:00:52.300
to do a really intensive ebook
workshop thanks to generous funding

00:00:52.300 --> 00:00:53.930
from the [inaudible] Foundation.

00:00:53.930 --> 00:00:56.590
And a lot of good work
came out of that.

00:00:56.590 --> 00:00:59.850
I think most importantly I got
hired, so hold your applause.

00:00:59.850 --> 00:01:07.640 position:56%
And so I wanted to give you at least
a quick update on where we are,

00:01:07.640 --> 00:01:12.050
and then introduce my colleagues
who will talk more of the state

00:01:12.050 --> 00:01:15.550
of ebooks and libraries
more broadly.

00:01:15.550 --> 00:01:20.460
So where are we now a
year after DPLA Fest 2015?

00:01:20.460 --> 00:01:23.660
I've got a couple of our projects

00:01:23.660 --> 00:01:26.350
that DPLA has been
working on up there.

00:01:26.350 --> 00:01:29.590
Open Ebooks has been mentioned
I know quite a few times today

00:01:29.590 --> 00:01:32.210
and we're going to talk about
it even more as we go through.

00:01:32.210 --> 00:01:35.160
And I'm sure that Micah's probably
going to talk about that as well.

00:01:35.160 --> 00:01:37.760
I'll just mention briefly
what DPLA's role has been

00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:39.790
in Open Ebooks as a partner.

00:01:39.790 --> 00:01:44.480
We put together a curation core of
the nation's top school librarians,

00:01:44.480 --> 00:01:49.260
librarians working with youth,
and they curated the 6,000 books

00:01:49.260 --> 00:01:51.180
that we have available
in Open Ebooks.

00:01:51.180 --> 00:01:53.280
They were able to take those
publisher donations and pick

00:01:53.280 --> 00:01:55.570
out what it is that
students really want as well

00:01:55.570 --> 00:01:58.940
as reflect the diversity.

00:01:58.940 --> 00:02:01.400 position:56%
We also run the social media for it,

00:02:01.400 --> 00:02:03.500
we help convene the community
conversations around it,

00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:07.190
we're helping to lead conversations
around accessibility in ebooks,

00:02:07.190 --> 00:02:10.750 position:56%
and try to improve even more some of
that native functionality that comes

00:02:10.750 --> 00:02:12.980
through ePUB and working
with Readium.

00:02:12.980 --> 00:02:16.450 position:56%
And we really see that all of the
press that's been around Open Ebooks

00:02:16.450 --> 00:02:18.870
as an opportunity to
help further some

00:02:18.870 --> 00:02:20.650
of these initiatives
in the ebook community.

00:02:20.650 --> 00:02:23.700
And DPLA is helping to lead
that conversation along

00:02:23.700 --> 00:02:27.520
with our partners NYPL
and First Books.

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:30.020
Also, I have up there a
little graphic for LEAP,

00:02:30.020 --> 00:02:33.930
the Library eContent Access
Project, which is funded by IMLS.

00:02:33.930 --> 00:02:37.790
And DPLA's role in that is to be
the, again, the community convener.

00:02:37.790 --> 00:02:41.160
We're trying to figure out what
our role is in ebooks again

00:02:41.160 --> 00:02:44.640
as we've worked in the past
year, and so we're helping

00:02:44.640 --> 00:02:47.880
to organize the conversations
that are going to go

00:02:47.880 --> 00:02:50.690
around creating a library-owned
marketplace

00:02:50.690 --> 00:02:54.180
which again Micah's going
to talk to a bit more later.

00:02:54.180 --> 00:02:59.120
With that idea though, and
DPLA organizing these community

00:02:59.120 --> 00:03:01.300
conversations, we're
also working on a sort

00:03:01.300 --> 00:03:05.540
of broader ebook working group,
a broader ebook community,

00:03:05.540 --> 00:03:08.100
and this came out of the
conversations last year.

00:03:08.100 --> 00:03:13.380 position:56%
So how can we create an umbrella for
everybody who's working in ebooks

00:03:13.380 --> 00:03:15.730
to come together and share
all of their information,

00:03:15.730 --> 00:03:17.370
share what they're working on?

00:03:17.370 --> 00:03:19.160
We want to be able to
streamline the effort.

00:03:19.160 --> 00:03:21.850
If somebody in Massachusetts
is working with a publisher

00:03:21.850 --> 00:03:23.250
and somebody in Texas is working

00:03:23.250 --> 00:03:26.010
with a publisher how can we make
sure that they're connecting

00:03:26.010 --> 00:03:27.470
with each other and talking

00:03:27.470 --> 00:03:31.380
about what [inaudible] they
were able to make with content.

00:03:31.380 --> 00:03:34.500
We had some great discussions
over the last week for those of us

00:03:34.500 --> 00:03:37.890
who were able to join at the Public
Library Association as well as some

00:03:37.890 --> 00:03:42.860 position:56%
of us got together yesterday as the
LEAP partners, and are really trying

00:03:42.860 --> 00:03:46.090
to see where we all fit in there.

00:03:46.090 --> 00:03:49.240 position:56%
And I think that those
conversations are going really well.

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:51.150
I also have a little
graphic down there.

00:03:51.150 --> 00:03:55.960
DPLA has about two million items
that are categorized as books

00:03:55.960 --> 00:04:01.830
within our site, and we're looking
at how we can open up that content.

00:04:01.830 --> 00:04:05.660
And there's going to be a whole
session right after this talking

00:04:05.660 --> 00:04:08.920
about how we can try to open up
the content that our hubs have

00:04:08.920 --> 00:04:12.750
and turn those into
accessible ebooks.

00:04:12.750 --> 00:04:15.440
So I'll just quickly add
going back to what I said

00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:18.940
about the ebook working group,
we want voices to get involved.

00:04:18.940 --> 00:04:21.740
We want people to feel that they
have a community that they can come

00:04:21.740 --> 00:04:23.850
into and talk about
ebooks, learn more,

00:04:23.850 --> 00:04:26.920
be connected with the resources
that they need for their library.

00:04:26.920 --> 00:04:32.520
So we have up here on the screen
a couple of different places

00:04:32.520 --> 00:04:34.060
where you can look to get involved.

00:04:34.060 --> 00:04:35.930
We're still sort of figuring

00:04:35.930 --> 00:04:38.990
out what our best options
are going to be.

00:04:38.990 --> 00:04:42.490
We've got a Google Plus
community, a working group listserv

00:04:42.490 --> 00:04:47.430
and a Wiki page that posts our
findings, our final products.

00:04:47.430 --> 00:04:52.540 position:56%
I would recommend going again to the
dp.la website, Get Involved, Ebooks.

00:04:52.540 --> 00:04:55.450
We're really trying to
get this to bubble up

00:04:55.450 --> 00:04:58.540
and making it easier
for you all to connect.

00:04:58.540 --> 00:05:01.330
So please just get in touch with
me if you know that you want

00:05:01.330 --> 00:05:03.890
to be involved, if it's a
conversation that you want

00:05:03.890 --> 00:05:06.520
to be part of and I can make
sure that you are plugged in.

00:05:06.520 --> 00:05:07.820
I'm Michelle.

00:05:07.820 --> 00:05:09.490 position:56%
You can find me on the DPLA website.

00:05:09.490 --> 00:05:12.000
Our emails are pretty easy.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:15.630
So with that I'll introduce
my colleagues who are here

00:05:15.630 --> 00:05:17.980
to give you an update from
their world of ebooks.

00:05:17.980 --> 00:05:21.620
We have Christine Peterson who
is the Amigos eShelf Manager

00:05:21.620 --> 00:05:24.430
for Amigos Library
Services in Texas.

00:05:24.430 --> 00:05:25.730
Greg Pronevitz.

00:05:25.730 --> 00:05:28.210
Oops, you guys switched
seats, spots on me.

00:05:28.210 --> 00:05:30.810
Greg Pronevitz on the end there
who is the Executive Director

00:05:30.810 --> 00:05:33.110 position:56%
of the Massachusetts Library System.

00:05:33.110 --> 00:05:35.740
And Micah May who is the
Director of Business Development

00:05:35.740 --> 00:05:38.160
for the New York Public Library.

00:05:38.160 --> 00:05:40.970
And with that I'll pass
it over to Christine.

00:05:47.280 --> 00:05:48.580
&gt;&gt; Christine Peterson:
Thanks for coming.

00:05:48.580 --> 00:05:49.880
I am Chris Peterson.

00:05:49.880 --> 00:05:53.920
I'm the Project Manager or Program
Manager for Amigos eShelf Project.

00:05:53.920 --> 00:05:56.540
But fortunately or
unfortunately I'm not here to talk

00:05:56.540 --> 00:05:57.840
to you about our project.

00:05:57.840 --> 00:05:59.140
Talk to me afterwards.

00:05:59.140 --> 00:06:01.090
Okay? No laughter?

00:06:01.090 --> 00:06:02.740
No nothing?

00:06:02.740 --> 00:06:05.090
[ Laughter ]

00:06:05.090 --> 00:06:10.120
Okay. So my role today is actually
not to talk to you about us

00:06:10.120 --> 00:06:11.970
but to give you a little
bit of history,

00:06:11.970 --> 00:06:15.600
to give you the library-created
platforms that went before us

00:06:15.600 --> 00:06:17.350
and where they are right now.

00:06:17.350 --> 00:06:19.200
But first I want to give
you the three reasons

00:06:19.200 --> 00:06:20.680
that libraries started doing this.

00:06:20.680 --> 00:06:23.170
And it really goes down to
Douglas County which I will talk

00:06:23.170 --> 00:06:24.940
about a little bit more in detail.

00:06:24.940 --> 00:06:27.010
There were three reasons
that Douglas County decided

00:06:27.010 --> 00:06:28.910
to create their own
instead of continue

00:06:28.910 --> 00:06:30.320
with the commercial vendors.

00:06:30.320 --> 00:06:32.750
The first was the loss of
ownership of the titles

00:06:32.750 --> 00:06:35.480
that they were subscribing
to at the time.

00:06:35.480 --> 00:06:37.400
Also, the increased price.

00:06:37.400 --> 00:06:39.890
There was a specific
incidence with OverDrive

00:06:39.890 --> 00:06:42.470
that really turned
the corner for them.

00:06:42.470 --> 00:06:45.850
And the third was the requirement
of their patrons having to learn

00:06:45.850 --> 00:06:47.810
yet another user interface.

00:06:47.810 --> 00:06:51.820
And with all three of those things
they decided we can do this.

00:06:51.820 --> 00:06:55.900
And so I'm going to start with
Douglas County who's our first.

00:06:55.900 --> 00:06:59.740
Douglas County decided to integrate
their ebooks into their ILS,

00:06:59.740 --> 00:07:01.920
the one you're looking
at right here.

00:07:01.920 --> 00:07:05.030
I have about a minute per
here so I'm going to move

00:07:05.030 --> 00:07:06.440
through these pretty quickly.

00:07:06.440 --> 00:07:08.630
They were the first ones that
said, "You know, we can do this."

00:07:08.630 --> 00:07:11.760
And they went to IMLS and
they were fortunate enough

00:07:11.760 --> 00:07:15.340
to get an IMLS grant to
help fund this change.

00:07:15.340 --> 00:07:19.250
They did decide to do what we all
claim we want to do which is try

00:07:19.250 --> 00:07:22.740 position:56%
to bring everything together instead
of having silos and they were able

00:07:22.740 --> 00:07:25.290
to bring everything
together within their ILS.

00:07:25.290 --> 00:07:28.340
Of course, they had
technical resources

00:07:28.340 --> 00:07:30.620
to be able to back that up.

00:07:30.620 --> 00:07:32.480
So the question is where
are they right now.

00:07:32.480 --> 00:07:34.760
Oh, by the way, everything
they did was open source.

00:07:34.760 --> 00:07:37.770
If you go to the Evoke--
e, v, o, k, e--

00:07:37.770 --> 00:07:39.870
website you will get
everything you need

00:07:39.870 --> 00:07:42.310
to know to do this for yourself.

00:07:42.310 --> 00:07:45.520
I do want to tell you that
where they are now is kind

00:07:45.520 --> 00:07:46.820
of questionable.

00:07:46.820 --> 00:07:49.750
Actually it's probably
not really questionable.

00:07:49.750 --> 00:07:51.370
They are not moving forward.

00:07:51.370 --> 00:07:53.350
There have been a number
of staffing changes

00:07:53.350 --> 00:07:57.850
at Douglas County particularly
in the administrative area,

00:07:57.850 --> 00:08:01.550
and their focus has been
moved to something else.

00:08:01.550 --> 00:08:04.610
Now I say that telling you
that they still have a server,

00:08:04.610 --> 00:08:07.350
an Adobe content server, sitting
there and it is still working.

00:08:07.350 --> 00:08:11.100 position:56%
They have not yet turned it off but
they are not moving forward with it.

00:08:11.100 --> 00:08:13.670
I also want to make mention here

00:08:13.670 --> 00:08:15.910
that when they created
this they created it

00:08:15.910 --> 00:08:17.510
without web-based ordering.

00:08:17.510 --> 00:08:22.330
I'll come back to that
explaining why that's important.

00:08:22.330 --> 00:08:25.580
Right after that, well, within
a year after that, Marmot,

00:08:25.580 --> 00:08:28.290
which is a consortium that
includes Douglas County,

00:08:28.290 --> 00:08:30.640
it's a multi-type library
consortium in Colorado,

00:08:30.640 --> 00:08:33.480
they decided to move
forward on this.

00:08:33.480 --> 00:08:34.920
And they created their own.

00:08:34.920 --> 00:08:37.380
Now they're a consortium so
they were not just dealing

00:08:37.380 --> 00:08:39.630 position:56%
with a single library at this point.

00:08:39.630 --> 00:08:41.990
They decided to use View Find,

00:08:41.990 --> 00:08:46.550
which is an open source discovery
system, as their interface.

00:08:46.550 --> 00:08:49.110
So they already had an existing ILS

00:08:49.110 --> 00:08:52.130
but they used View Find
as that discovery piece.

00:08:52.130 --> 00:08:55.780
So that when they added the ebooks
they were also doing the same thing

00:08:55.780 --> 00:08:58.390
as Douglas County they were
just doing it the different way.

00:08:58.390 --> 00:09:02.880 position:56%
Douglas County used their ILS,
Marmot used the View Find interface.

00:09:02.880 --> 00:09:07.970
So they already had a very
robust ILS that was going.

00:09:07.970 --> 00:09:10.830 position:56%
They went ahead and included ebooks.

00:09:10.830 --> 00:09:13.590
They also integrated
ebooks with other resources.

00:09:13.590 --> 00:09:15.830
They are not just dealing
with OverDrive.

00:09:15.830 --> 00:09:17.770
They deal with multiple
ebook aggregators

00:09:17.770 --> 00:09:19.270
and they bring all
of that in to one.

00:09:19.270 --> 00:09:21.620
They do an incredible job there.

00:09:21.620 --> 00:09:24.340
They also upgraded the
View Find functionality

00:09:24.340 --> 00:09:25.640
so much that it forked.

00:09:25.640 --> 00:09:27.930
So now you have View Find Plus

00:09:27.930 --> 00:09:31.240
and you have the View
Find Community versions.

00:09:31.240 --> 00:09:35.980
They also have decided not to
move forward with the ebook side

00:09:35.980 --> 00:09:38.920
of this with the platform side.

00:09:38.920 --> 00:09:42.190
Mainly because they're
changing their focus,

00:09:42.190 --> 00:09:45.530
and into other types
of functionality.

00:09:45.530 --> 00:09:49.170
Now the interesting thing is
their Adobe content server sits

00:09:49.170 --> 00:09:50.810
at Douglas County.

00:09:50.810 --> 00:09:52.230
They share that server.

00:09:52.230 --> 00:09:55.920
So as long as Douglas County's
server is up Marmot is still up

00:09:55.920 --> 00:09:58.340
but they're just not doing
anything with the service.

00:09:58.340 --> 00:10:01.840
I don't believe, last time I
heard there was not a timeframe

00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:04.530
for Douglas County to take that
server down but I would imagine

00:10:04.530 --> 00:10:06.890
in the next year it might be down.

00:10:06.890 --> 00:10:10.290 position:56%
Marmot is right now starting to move
those ebooks that they purchased

00:10:10.290 --> 00:10:15.180
on to other commercial platforms
that they have access to.

00:10:15.180 --> 00:10:21.310
Taking a little bit out of, I was
trying to do from oldest to newest

00:10:21.310 --> 00:10:23.090
but I want to continue
with Colorado.

00:10:23.090 --> 00:10:25.310
This is probably one
of the newer projects.

00:10:25.310 --> 00:10:27.620
This is the Evoke 2.0 Project.

00:10:27.620 --> 00:10:30.520
And the reason Colorado did
this was because of the lack

00:10:30.520 --> 00:10:32.730
of web-based ordering which
made it really difficult

00:10:32.730 --> 00:10:35.390
for the smaller libraries
to be able to join.

00:10:35.390 --> 00:10:38.900
Too much time, they didn't
have the resources to do it.

00:10:38.900 --> 00:10:42.170
So they went back to
IMLS and got a grant

00:10:42.170 --> 00:10:45.460
to actually create an
end-to-end solution

00:10:45.460 --> 00:10:48.050
which included not
only web-based ordering

00:10:48.050 --> 00:10:50.120
but also included a
really nice interface.

00:10:50.120 --> 00:10:53.260
It was a compliment to the projects

00:10:53.260 --> 00:10:55.990
that had already been
going on in Colorado.

00:10:55.990 --> 00:11:01.800
And they did do this, they
got an agreement with Odilo

00:11:01.800 --> 00:11:06.060
and Odilo went ahead and changed
their software to do this.

00:11:06.060 --> 00:11:08.520
Unfortunately it was
never implemented.

00:11:08.520 --> 00:11:11.300
So it sits in Colorado
and right now it sits

00:11:11.300 --> 00:11:13.250
at the Colorado State Library.

00:11:13.250 --> 00:11:15.610
To this point nothing
has been done with it.

00:11:15.610 --> 00:11:17.130
That doesn't mean that
something won't be.

00:11:17.130 --> 00:11:21.320
But right now it's been a
year, maybe a little bit more,

00:11:21.320 --> 00:11:23.290
that the software hasn't been used.

00:11:23.290 --> 00:11:25.200
So we don't know where
this one is going.

00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:26.980
We'll see.

00:11:26.980 --> 00:11:28.280
I know that there's
a lot of interest

00:11:28.280 --> 00:11:30.850
at the Colorado State Library to
do something with it and to be part

00:11:30.850 --> 00:11:35.310 position:56%
of the ebook work that's being done.

00:11:35.310 --> 00:11:43.880 position:56%
The next group that came forward was
sorry, was Califa, sorry about that.

00:11:43.880 --> 00:11:46.910
Califa is a consortium
out of California.

00:11:46.910 --> 00:11:48.770
It's a public library consortium.

00:11:48.770 --> 00:11:52.130
And they are the third.

00:11:52.130 --> 00:11:54.310
So we have Douglas County, we have
Marmot and then we have Califa.

00:11:54.310 --> 00:11:57.580 position:56%
And all of these people I'm talking
about, you know those of us who came

00:11:57.580 --> 00:11:59.630
after stand on the
shoulders of these people.

00:11:59.630 --> 00:12:01.100
I mean they did incredible work.

00:12:01.100 --> 00:12:04.960
They did incredible time,
experience, money that went

00:12:04.960 --> 00:12:07.160
into this so even though
I'm telling you that some

00:12:07.160 --> 00:12:09.790
of these projects have
stopped that doesn't mean

00:12:09.790 --> 00:12:12.670
that we don't still value
the work that they did,

00:12:12.670 --> 00:12:14.410
and that continues with Califa.

00:12:14.410 --> 00:12:17.220
So they are a consortium.

00:12:17.220 --> 00:12:21.420
There are multiple ILSs there
that they work through and with.

00:12:21.420 --> 00:12:25.000
They use the View Find interface
that Marmot has created.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:28.630
They also started out with
a single-shared collection

00:12:28.630 --> 00:12:31.730
and now they have moved to not
only a single-shared collection

00:12:31.730 --> 00:12:34.270
but also collections
for each library.

00:12:34.270 --> 00:12:35.650
You might notice that
I have a note up there

00:12:35.650 --> 00:12:37.620
that the Kansas State
Library is part of Califa.

00:12:37.620 --> 00:12:40.760
And so those of you who are in the
know know that there was an issue

00:12:40.760 --> 00:12:44.610
between Califa, I mean, sorry,
Kansas State Library and OverDrive

00:12:44.610 --> 00:12:48.560
when OverDrive upped their
cost by 700% the result

00:12:48.560 --> 00:12:51.080
of that was Kansas
pulled their books out,

00:12:51.080 --> 00:12:53.170
and they are now a Califa member.

00:12:53.170 --> 00:12:58.430
