00:32:33.760 --> 00:32:36.630
across library worlds and this
will start to become very real.

00:32:36.630 --> 00:32:40.970
So that's ready in the sense that
the technology is up, it's working,

00:32:40.970 --> 00:32:45.370
it's proving to be very scalable
in Open Ebooks implementation.

00:32:45.370 --> 00:32:49.240
And it is designed to be open
source and is inexpensive

00:32:49.240 --> 00:32:51.040 position:56%
as possible for libraries to deploy.

00:32:51.040 --> 00:32:54.290
And the first step in them
beginning to take ownership

00:32:54.290 --> 00:32:56.010
of their relationship
with their patrons.

00:32:56.010 --> 00:32:58.960
And I guess sort of philosophically
I'd like to emphasize

00:32:58.960 --> 00:33:00.290
that that's why we started here.

00:33:00.290 --> 00:33:02.730
It is the app through
which people read.

00:33:02.730 --> 00:33:05.480
It is the primary mechanism
for discovery.

00:33:05.480 --> 00:33:09.060
It's the touch point where
we interact with our patrons.

00:33:09.060 --> 00:33:11.550
And what we wanted to
start with is the assertion

00:33:11.550 --> 00:33:15.730 position:56%
that these patrons are our patrons,
our customers and our relationships.

00:33:15.730 --> 00:33:19.460
And our vendors sometimes would
like to both sell us content

00:33:19.460 --> 00:33:20.760
and own that relationship.

00:33:20.760 --> 00:33:25.500
And I think we have begun to reject
that and say, "If a library chooses

00:33:25.500 --> 00:33:28.900
to provide these services through
a vendor-hosted offering then

00:33:28.900 --> 00:33:30.720
that is fine if it's
the libraries choice."

00:33:30.720 --> 00:33:32.700
But that cannot be our only option.

00:33:32.700 --> 00:33:35.010
We as libraries have
the right and the need

00:33:35.010 --> 00:33:39.600
to have the interoperability that
supports us in serving libraries

00:33:39.600 --> 00:33:41.690
in an environment we
own and we control.

00:33:41.690 --> 00:33:44.590
And I think SimplyE is the
vehicle for that right now.

00:33:44.590 --> 00:33:47.950
So it allows us both to merge
all of our ebook content

00:33:47.950 --> 00:33:52.210
from multiple distributors into one
place so that we can rationalize it

00:33:52.210 --> 00:33:55.030
and put it all in one place,
which in turns allows us

00:33:55.030 --> 00:33:59.590
to free our procurement
decisions of the user experience

00:33:59.590 --> 00:34:02.420
so that we can buy from whomever
gives us the best deal whenever we

00:34:02.420 --> 00:34:05.050
want, and that will drive
competition in the market.

00:34:05.050 --> 00:34:08.910
And I think in some ways even
more exciting and powerful

00:34:08.910 --> 00:34:12.450
than what SimplyE can do today is
what it's going to be able to do

00:34:12.450 --> 00:34:16.090
to tomorrow, which is that because
we own it we can do what want

00:34:16.090 --> 00:34:17.390
with it.

00:34:17.390 --> 00:34:20.130
If libraries want to come together
and say that it's really critical

00:34:20.130 --> 00:34:23.720
to be able to ingest an API feed
about programs we're running

00:34:23.720 --> 00:34:27.950
in our branches so that we can have
push marketing and there's a pop-up

00:34:27.950 --> 00:34:30.880
in your ereader saying,
"We're running our program

00:34:30.880 --> 00:34:32.530
in a branch five blocks from you.

00:34:32.530 --> 00:34:34.440
In half an hour please come join."

00:34:34.440 --> 00:34:36.070
That's something that
we can fully build now

00:34:36.070 --> 00:34:38.540
because this is our
experience and we own it.

00:34:38.540 --> 00:34:42.030
This is providing library service
through library-owned channels

00:34:42.030 --> 00:34:45.650
which I think is really the
point of all of this work.

00:34:45.650 --> 00:34:50.930
So briefly, specifically, SimplyE
right now today can integrate

00:34:50.930 --> 00:34:53.910
through middleware collections
that libraries own and host

00:34:53.910 --> 00:34:57.690
on the three major
existing library vendors--

00:34:57.690 --> 00:35:01.730
3M Bibliotheca, Baker and Taylor,
and OverDrive, the BiblioBoards

00:35:01.730 --> 00:35:04.800
or Biblio [inaudible] API is
within weeks of being finished.

00:35:04.800 --> 00:35:08.550
And then that, too, this year
will be able to be integrated.

00:35:08.550 --> 00:35:13.920
And so we continue to have more
and more content that we can roll

00:35:13.920 --> 00:35:17.230
into one better comprehensive
experience.

00:35:17.230 --> 00:35:19.450
And I'd like to go
back to Greg's slide

00:35:19.450 --> 00:35:22.710
about the other ebook platforms.

00:35:22.710 --> 00:35:26.040 position:56%
I think we've really turned a corner
in the last three years in that

00:35:26.040 --> 00:35:29.600 position:56%
as I talk to other distributors, so
EBSCO is a standout example of this,

00:35:29.600 --> 00:35:33.180
they were second on Greg's slide,
they're many state libraries,

00:35:33.180 --> 00:35:35.520
many consortia and many
individual libraries

00:35:35.520 --> 00:35:37.020
who own ebook collections
through EBSCO.

00:35:37.020 --> 00:35:39.580
Now EBSCO does not
yet have a content API

00:35:39.580 --> 00:35:42.100
so it would be impossible
to merge their content

00:35:42.100 --> 00:35:43.670
into anything but their app.

00:35:43.670 --> 00:35:47.080 position:56%
But in conversations with them in
the last month it's been clear to me

00:35:47.080 --> 00:35:49.370
that we're in a very
different place.

00:35:49.370 --> 00:35:52.780
So in 2012 these distributors
refused to build the APIs.

00:35:52.780 --> 00:35:55.970
And we were trying to beat
and bludgeon and negotiate,

00:35:55.970 --> 00:35:57.300
and we still kind of failed.

00:35:57.300 --> 00:35:59.190
And then we started
ReadersFirst with others

00:35:59.190 --> 00:36:03.030
that had the same experience,
the demand access to our content.

00:36:03.030 --> 00:36:04.330
We're not there anymore.

00:36:04.330 --> 00:36:08.030 position:56%
So if you talk to EBSCO they will
tell you that they're perfectly open

00:36:08.030 --> 00:36:09.330
to building a content API.

00:36:09.330 --> 00:36:11.250
They plan to do it and they're
willing to build to our spec

00:36:11.250 --> 00:36:13.050
so that we can make
these interoperable.

00:36:13.050 --> 00:36:16.630
And that is an example of
this ReadersFirst application

00:36:16.630 --> 00:36:19.600
that is the underpinning to be
able to doing any of this work.

00:36:19.600 --> 00:36:22.800 position:56%
So I think one of the most important
thing that libraries are interested

00:36:22.800 --> 00:36:25.840
in this and need to do is to
start talking to their vendors

00:36:25.840 --> 00:36:28.510
