00:40:31.280 --> 00:40:33.660
Anyone feeling brave and want
to step up and volunteer?

00:40:33.660 --> 00:40:36.220
Why did you come to this talk?

00:40:36.220 --> 00:40:38.710
What gets you excited about this?

00:40:48.120 --> 00:40:52.170
Yeah. Thanks Michael.

00:40:54.340 --> 00:40:55.730
&gt;&gt; Michael: [inaudible]
thank you very much.

00:40:55.730 --> 00:40:57.260
It's certainly very exciting.

00:40:57.260 --> 00:41:00.310
I think that libraries have
learned in the last ten years

00:41:00.310 --> 00:41:02.000
that branding is essential
and this is going

00:41:02.000 --> 00:41:04.020
to be an opportunity
for us to do that.

00:41:04.020 --> 00:41:11.580
Second thing is it has been
too difficult for library users

00:41:11.580 --> 00:41:16.100
to get access to content in
many cases, ebook content,

00:41:16.100 --> 00:41:20.130
and if we can simplify that
and provide a better model

00:41:20.130 --> 00:41:23.240
for the publishers to work with us

00:41:23.240 --> 00:41:27.430
that we will see continuing
exponential increases

00:41:27.430 --> 00:41:29.810
in library ebooks.

00:41:29.810 --> 00:41:34.440
And libraries are not ebooks
only its econtent, and this is

00:41:34.440 --> 00:41:38.060
yet another way to make ourselves
more relevant and present

00:41:38.060 --> 00:41:40.500
in an increasingly digital world.

00:41:40.500 --> 00:41:42.320
&gt;&gt; Micah May: I think
that's exactly right.

00:41:42.320 --> 00:41:46.640
We need to own this
from every angle.

00:41:46.640 --> 00:41:48.520
If I'm not seeing other
hands I guess I'd love

00:41:48.520 --> 00:41:49.820
to build on that publisher point.

00:41:49.820 --> 00:41:51.880
I think many of us have
talked about the need

00:41:51.880 --> 00:41:53.880
to evolve relationships
with publishers.

00:41:53.880 --> 00:41:56.460
And I think again projects
like Amigos

00:41:56.460 --> 00:41:59.470
and Califa have been broken
tremendous ground there in showing

00:41:59.470 --> 00:42:02.310
that smaller publishers are
willing to work directly even

00:42:02.310 --> 00:42:05.550
with regional library associations,

00:42:05.550 --> 00:42:07.810
and make their books available
through those platforms.

00:42:07.810 --> 00:42:09.990
I think one of the goals
of the LEAP Project

00:42:09.990 --> 00:42:13.460
which is completely supportive
of that and hopefully consistent

00:42:13.460 --> 00:42:15.990
with it is to allow
libraries all over the country

00:42:15.990 --> 00:42:19.130
and library organizations like
Califa and Amigos to onboard

00:42:19.130 --> 00:42:21.240
that content to a national
marketplace.

00:42:21.240 --> 00:42:24.710
So that we can not only buy content
on better terms but we can help

00:42:24.710 --> 00:42:27.530
to bring those relationships
into existence

00:42:27.530 --> 00:42:31.230
so that we can offer a more diverse
and a broader range of content

00:42:31.230 --> 00:42:33.940
And then the second piece of that
is about getting to better terms.

00:42:33.940 --> 00:42:36.800
And I think we have begun to
show that that's also possible.

00:42:36.800 --> 00:42:40.770
Examples like Open Ebooks whereby
presenting the library values-based

00:42:40.770 --> 00:42:44.080
argument we were able to get
these incredible donations

00:42:44.080 --> 00:42:46.410
that are now making this
content free to low income.

00:42:46.410 --> 00:42:50.200
But also other work of the ALA
Digital Content Working Group,

00:42:50.200 --> 00:42:52.340
and actually NYPL directly pushing

00:42:52.340 --> 00:42:54.350
with libraries I think
multiple voices

00:42:54.350 --> 00:42:58.000 position:56%
from the library community have
helped both to bring libraries back,

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:00.560
or publishers back into
the library market in 2012,

00:43:00.560 --> 00:43:04.620
and can now go further in working
directly with those publishers

00:43:04.620 --> 00:43:05.970
to get us the better deals.

00:43:05.970 --> 00:43:08.770
And I think that's one of the
important points about why we need

00:43:08.770 --> 00:43:12.030
to take ownership of this whole
pipeline, this whole channel

00:43:12.030 --> 00:43:14.900
because it's pretty clear
to many of us I think

00:43:14.900 --> 00:43:16.370
that the commercial distributors

00:43:16.370 --> 00:43:19.080
from whom we buy books their
incentives are just not

00:43:19.080 --> 00:43:20.380
well aligned.

00:43:20.380 --> 00:43:22.560
If we get a better price term,
if we get a better term in terms

00:43:22.560 --> 00:43:25.030
of options they don't
make any more money.

00:43:25.030 --> 00:43:26.970
And that just, in fact, costs
them money because now they have

00:43:26.970 --> 00:43:29.870
to go redoing their systems
to accommodate that term.

00:43:29.870 --> 00:43:34.220
So we need an advocate that
is a sophisticated sort

00:43:34.220 --> 00:43:36.450
of a business advocate to deal

00:43:36.450 --> 00:43:38.330
with publishers especially
the biggest publishers.

00:43:38.330 --> 00:43:40.350
And I think we can also
benefit tremendously

00:43:40.350 --> 00:43:43.670
from a distributed capacity
that allows libraries all

00:43:43.670 --> 00:43:47.970
over the country to be not only a
provider of content but a channel

00:43:47.970 --> 00:43:50.880
for making content discoverable
and available in libraries

00:43:50.880 --> 00:43:53.570
by working directly with
publishers, and potentially

00:43:53.570 --> 00:43:57.360
in the future even authors in
their region to bring that content

00:43:57.360 --> 00:44:00.990
into libraries and to
make it discovered.

